  "response": "When a test passes in isolation but fails in a full test suite, this typically indicates either test order dependency or shared global state issues. Here's how to systematically isolate the problem:\n\n1. **Identify the failing test**\n   - Run the full test suite with verbose output to identify exactly which test is failing\n   - Note any error messages and stack traces\n\n2. **Test order dependency investigation**\n   - Run the failing test immediately after each other test individually\n   - If you find a specific test that when run before the failing test causes failure, you've identified an order dependency\n   - Use test framework features to force execution order (like `--seed` in RSpec or `--order` in Jest)\n\n3. **Shared global state investigation**\n   - Look for static/class variables, singletons, or global objects\n   - Check for environment variables being modified\n   - Examine database state if applicable\n   - Look for file system interactions or shared resources\n\n4. **Isolation techniques**\n   - Add setup/teardown code to reset the environment between tests\n   - Mock external dependencies\n   - Use database transactions or truncation between tests\n   - Reset any modified environment variables\n\n5. **Fix strategies**\n   - For order dependencies: ensure proper setup/teardown in each test\n   - For shared state: implement proper isolation or state reset between tests\n   - Consider refactoring tests to avoid dependencies altogether",
