  "response": "# Decision Policy: Reliability vs. Delivery Speed Under Deadline Pressure\n\n## Purpose\nThis policy provides a structured framework for determining when to prioritize reliability over delivery speed when facing deadline constraints.\n\n## Core Principles\n1. **Customer Impact**: Higher potential negative impact on customers increases reliability priority\n2. **System Criticality**: Core systems require higher reliability standards\n3. **Recovery Capability**: Systems with limited rollback options demand greater reliability\n4. **Risk Assessment**: Decisions should be data-driven based on quantifiable risks\n\n## Decision Matrix\n\n| Factor | Reliability Priority | Speed Priority |\n|--------|---------------------|----------------|\n| **System Type** | Mission-critical, financial, security, health/safety systems | Internal tools, non-critical features, easily reversible changes |\n| **User Impact** | Large user base affected, significant user workflow disruption | Limited user exposure, minimal workflow impact, alternative paths available |\n| **Failure Consequence** | Data loss, security breach, regulatory violation, significant financial loss | Minor inconvenience, cosmetic issues, easily recoverable errors |\n| **Monitoring Capability** | Limited visibility into system health, delayed detection | Robust monitoring, quick detection and alerting |\n| **Recovery Options** | Complex rollback, extended recovery time, data restoration challenges | Simple rollback, quick recovery, no data integrity concerns |\n| **Business Context** | Regulatory deadlines, contractual obligations, security patches | Marketing events, competitive response, internal milestones |\n\n## Decision Process\n1. **Assess Factors**: Evaluate each factor in the decision matrix\n2. **Calculate Risk Score**: Assign weights to factors based on organizational priorities\n3. **Set Thresholds**: Define clear risk thresholds that trigger reliability prioritization\n4. **Document Decision**